1428","1297–1389":"1297–1389","1299–1393":"1299–1393","1389":"1389","1344":"1344","1299":"1299","1297":"1297","1393":"1393","1370":"1370","1428":"1428","England":"Anglie, United Kingdom","St Edmonds, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Anglie, United Kingdom","Yaxley, Suffolk, England":"Yaxley, Suffolk, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1344–1393":"1344–1393","1370–1428":"1370–1428","1297–1389":"1297–1389","1299–1393":"1299–1393","1389":"1389","1344":"1344","1299":"1299","1297":"1297","1393":"1393","1370":"1370","1428":"1428","England":"England, United Kingdom","St Edmonds, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Yaxley, Suffolk, England":"Yaxley, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1344–1393":"1344–1393","1370–1428":"1370–1428","1297–1389":"1297–1389","1299–1393":"1299–1393","1389":"1389","1344":"1344","1299":"1299","1297":"1297","1393":"1393","1370":"1370","1428":"1428","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","St Edmonds, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Yaxley, Suffolk, England":"Yaxley, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1344–1393":"1344–1393","1370–1428":"1370–1428","1297–1389":"1297–1389","1299–1393":"1299–1393","1389":"1389","1344":"1344","1299":"1299","1297":"1297","1393":"1393","1370":"1370","1428":"1428","England":"England, United Kingdom","St Edmonds, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Yaxley, Suffolk, England":"Yaxley, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fuller","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a dresser of cloth, from Middle English <i>fuller</i> ‘fuller of cloth’ (partly from Old English <i>fullere</i>, partly from Old French <i>fouleor</i>, <i>foleur</i>, Latin <i>fullo</i>). Raw cloth had to be fulled, i.e. scoured, cleansed, and thickened by beating or trampling it in water, a process also known as <i>walking</i> or <i>tucking</i>, hence the surnames   Walker   and   Tucker   alongside <i>Fuller</i>. These three terms and surnames are characteristic of different parts of England. In general, in Middle English, <i>Fuller</i> is southern and eastern, while <i>Walker</i> belongs to the west and north and <i>Tucker</i> is southwestern. Compare   Fullen  .","English: variant of   Fullard   with loss of <i>-d</i>.","German (<b>Füller</b>): occupational name for a person whose work involved filling, such as a dauber, or a nickname for a gourmand or glutton. Compare   Filler  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Walker","meanings":["English (mainly North and Midlands) and Scottish: occupational name for a fuller, from Middle English <i>walker</i>, Old English <i>wealcere</i> (an agent derivative of <i>wealcan</i> ‘to walk, tread’), ‘one who trampled cloth in a bath of lye or kneaded it, in order to strengthen it’. This was the regular term for the occupation during the Middle Ages in western and northern England. Compare   Fuller   and   Tucker  . As a Scottish surname it has also been used as a translation of Gaelic <b>Mac an Fhucadair</b> ‘son of the fuller’. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","History: The name was brought to North America from northern England and Scotland independently by many different bearers in the 17th and 18th centuries. Samuel Walker came to Lynn, MA, <i>c.</i> 1630; Philip Walker was in Rehoboth, MA, in or before 1643. The surname was also established in VA before 1650; a Thomas Walker, born in 1715 in King and Queen County, VA, was a physician, soldier, and explorer."]},{"name":"Filler","meanings":["South German: occupational name for a flayer or skinner, from Middle High German <i>viller</i> ‘knacker’, from <i>villen</i> ‘to skin’.","Altered form of German <b>Füller</b> (see   Fuller  ).","English: variant of   Filer   1 or 2."]},{"name":"Fullen","meanings":["English: occupational name for a fuller (see   Fuller  ), from Old French <i>fulun</i> ‘fuller’.","English (Lancashire): branch of this family in Lancashire probably represents a variant of <b>Fulham</b> (see   Fullam  ), reintroduced from Ireland."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Fuller was born in 1344, in Yaxley, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas Fulmer, was 47 and his mother, Margery, was 45. He had at least 1 daughter. He died in 1393, in his hometown, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1344–1393":"1344–1393","1370–1428":"1370–1428","1297–1389":"1297–1389","1299–1393":"1299–1393","1389":"1389","1344":"1344","1299":"1299","1297":"1297","1393":"1393","1370":"1370","1428":"1428","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","St Edmonds, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Yaxley, Suffolk, England":"Yaxley, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1344–1393":"1344–1393","1370–1428":"1370–1428","1297–1389":"1297–1389","1299–1393":"1299–1393","1389":"1389","1344":"1344","1299":"1299","1297":"1297","1393":"1393","1370":"1370","1428":"1428","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","St Edmonds, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Yaxley, Suffolk, England":"Yaxley, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1344–1393":"1344–1393","1370–1428":"1370–1428","1297–1389":"1297–1389","1299–1393":"1299–1393","1389":"1389","1344":"1344","1299":"1299","1297":"1297","1393":"1393","1370":"1370","1428":"1428","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","St Edmonds, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Y